find the terrorist in the Internet
haystack. Hell of a haystack.

21:37.240 --> 21:38.673
Hundreds of
terabytes a minute.

21:38.760 --> 21:41.672
I mean, it would take you 400
years to read the emails.

21:41.760 --> 21:43.796
Then you have
to analyze them.

21:44.600 --> 21:46.830
Sometimes, the more you
look, the less you see.

21:47.920 --> 21:49.816
- What'd you come up with?
- Something beautiful.

21:49.840 --> 21:52.229
In house.
For $3 million.

21:52.320 --> 21:56.393
A program that could differentiate
between foreign and domestic,

21:56.480 --> 22:00.109
encrypt every signal we weren't
targeting, so it would remain private.

22:00.360 --> 22:02.430
It was elegant, streamlined.

22:02.520 --> 22:04.351
It was the best
work I ever did.

22:05.920 --> 22:07.069
Have a seat.

22:08.720 --> 22:09.948
What was it called?

22:17.920 --> 22:23.119
Ed, rising to
the top in our world

22:23.200 --> 22:26.556
can sometimes
be hard on a man.

22:26.640 --> 22:30.997
I mean... You think
you're making strides,

22:31.120 --> 22:33.759
you think you're
taking the initiative.

22:34.600 --> 22:37.478
And then, the next minute, they
grind your work out of existence.

22:38.040 --> 22:40.031
They didn't use it?
Why not?

22:40.120 --> 22:42.509
Well,
they never tell you why.

22:44.040 --> 22:46.634
Two years later,
after 9/11,

22:46.760 --> 22:48.034
a friend of mine
tells me about

22:48.120 --> 22:50.918
this new contractor
program they're using.

22:51.000 --> 22:53.434
Costs $4 billion
to deploy.

22:53.520 --> 22:58.469
Modeled after mine but with
no filters, no automation.

22:59.560 --> 23:03.189
Ingested everything.
They were drowning in data.

23:03.280 --> 23:04.918
It was a fucking disaster.

23:05.000 --> 23:07.878
Okay, but there must have been
some bigger picture, right?

23:07.960 --> 23:11.270
I mean, spending that kind of money?
They're not stupid.

23:11.360 --> 23:13.999
You would think intelligence
would count for something

23:14.120 --> 23:15.951
in the intelligence
business.

23:16.080 --> 23:19.436
Right. But you wanna
know what it really is?

23:19.520 --> 23:21.715
What really sets
the agenda?

23:22.720 --> 23:27.111
Military industrial
happiness management.

23:28.040 --> 23:30.031
You keep the coffers
open in Congress,

23:30.120 --> 23:33.271
you keep the money flowing
to the contractors.

23:33.360 --> 23:37.069
Efficiency, results?
They go out the window.

23:37.920 --> 23:40.514
Not to mention...
All right.

23:42.000 --> 23:43.115
Well, you're late
for class.

23:44.800 --> 23:46.631
Okay. Thank you.

23:48.400 --> 23:50.789
Can I take another one?
Sure.

23:57.840 --> 24:00.400
Did you ever say
anything to anybody?

24:00.480 --> 24:04.598
Yeah. I went to legal.
We filed complaints.

24:04.680 --> 24:08.514
Now here I am,
tucked away, teaching you.

24:11.320 --> 24:13.754
Maybe that's more important,
in the long run.

24:14.640 --> 24:15.675
You're getting better.

24:31.560 --> 24:33.516
My favorite spot
on campus.

24:36.120 --> 24:37.599
You hunt, Ed?

24:38.720 --> 24:40.073
Uh...

24:40.920 --> 24:43.480
Did some skeet shooting
with my dad a few times,

24:43.560 --> 24:45.312
but, no,
I never went hunting.

24:45.400 --> 24:46.594
We'll go one day.

24:46.680 --> 24:47.908
That'd be great.

24:49.280 --> 24:50.952
Mr. O'Brian,
can I ask you a question?

24:51.040 --> 24:52.792
How about just
calling me Corbin?

24:53.160 --> 24:56.709
Okay.
Thank you, sir. Uh, Corbin.

24:57.680 --> 25:02.196
I was talking with Hank
Forrester and I wanted to know,

25:02.280 --> 25:06.159
are all of our SIGINT programs
specifically targeted?

25:06.920 --> 25:10.708
Of course. What good would
they be if they weren't? Hmm?

25:12.160 --> 25:13.559
Yeah, I don't know.

25:15.840 --> 25:17.671
You have a girlfriend, Ed?

25:19.880 --> 25:21.518
Uh, nothing serious.

25:21.600 --> 25:23.033
What's her name?
Lindsay.

25:23.120 --> 25:24.155
Lindsay.

25:25.440 --> 25:26.998
She going with you?

25:27.800 --> 25:30.633
No, I wouldn't want
to put her in any danger.

25:30.720 --> 25:31.789
Well, you won't have to.

25:32.160 --> 25:34.276
We're not sending you
to the Middle East.

25:39.600 --> 25:44.116
Sir, I'm your best student.
Doesn't that count for something?

25:44.960 --> 25:49.397
In 20 years, Iraq will be a
hellhole nobody cares about.

25:49.480 --> 25:51.516
Terrorism's
a short-term threat.

25:51.600 --> 25:56.116
The real threats will come
from China, Russia, Iran,

25:56.240 --> 25:59.038
and they'll come as
SQL injections and malware.

25:59.160 --> 26:03.233
Without minds like yours, this country
will be torn apart in cyberspace.

26:04.120 --> 26:05.473
I don't want to risk
losing you

26:05.600 --> 26:08.319
for some horseshit war
over sand and oil.

26:10.960 --> 26:12.837
Sir, I'm surprised
to hear you say that.

26:12.920 --> 26:16.276
You don't have to agree with your
politicians to be a patriot.

26:20.320 --> 26:22.788
Sir, where are you sending me?
Take a moment.

26:23.440 --> 26:24.839
Enjoy the view.

26:27.920 --> 26:28.920
Hey.

26:46.640 --> 26:47.834
This is Laura.

26:48.480 --> 26:49.480
Hello.

26:49.560 --> 26:51.039
Hello,
nice to meet you.

26:51.880 --> 26:54.997
Hello, I'm Ewen MacAskill from the
Guardian. It's nice to meet you.

26:55.080 --> 26:56.274
Nice to meet you, too.

26:56.360 --> 26:59.875
Um, if you don't mind, uh,
I'd like to record some of...

26:59.960 --> 27:02.315
Uh... Cell phones go
in the microwave.

27:02.720 --> 27:03.789
Dare I ask why?

27:03.880 --> 27:06.314
We'll get to that.
After you ask your questions.

27:07.320 --> 27:08.469
Yeah, before...

27:08.560 --> 27:10.696
Before we get on to the stories,
I need to know more about you.

27:10.720 --> 27:15.111
Your career by Glenn's account
is very varied,

27:15.200 --> 27:16.872
but the Guardian
needs evidence that...

27:16.960 --> 27:19.997
Yeah. This is my diplomatic
passport for friendly countries,

27:20.080 --> 27:21.957
my tourist passport
for everywhere else.

27:22.040 --> 27:23.439
You can check
the visa stamps.

27:23.520 --> 27:27.559
This is my NSA badge with Booz Allen,
my CIA badge with Dell,

27:27.640 --> 27:30.712
and this is my DIA
instructor's badge.

27:30.800 --> 27:33.712
This is a photo of me
with Michael Hayden,

27:33.880 --> 27:36.713
who's a former head
of the NSA and the CIA.

27:38.040 --> 27:39.155
When can you publish?

27:40.400 --> 27:43.631
Okay, um, do you mind if I sit down?
No, please.

27:43.920 --> 27:48.198
Uh, Glenn says
you want to, uh...

27:48.440 --> 27:50.237
You want to tell people
your identity.

27:50.320 --> 27:52.176
How do you think your
government's going to react?

27:52.200 --> 27:54.589
Well, they'll charge me
under the Espionage Act.

27:54.680 --> 27:57.399
And they'll say I endangered
national security,

27:57.480 --> 28:00.153
and they'll demonize me,
and my friends and family.

28:00.280 --> 28:02.999
And they'll throw me in jail.

28:03.080 --> 28:05.116
That's the
best-case scenario.

28:05.240 --> 28:06.514
And the worst?

28:06.600 --> 28:08.795
Well, if I don't
have any media cover,

28:08.880 --> 28:11.474
then I'll be rendered
by the CIA

28:11.560 --> 28:13.915
and interrogated
outside of the law.

28:14.000 --> 28:16.639
And they have a station
right up the street.

28:16.720 --> 28:19.109
But how would they
know what you did?

28:19.200 --> 28:22.749
Because I left a digital footprint in
my logs, so they'll figure it out.

28:22.840 --> 28:24.796
I did not want
a manhunt.

28:24.880 --> 28:27.030
I know what they would
do to my colleagues.

28:28.320 --> 28:31.153
Look, Mr. MacAskill, uh,

28:31.240 --> 28:34.835
this is not about money
or anything for me.

28:34.920 --> 28:36.148
There's no hidden agenda.

28:36.240 --> 28:40.028
I just wanted to get this data to
established journalists like yourselves,

28:40.120 --> 28:42.350
so that you can present it
to the world,

28:42.440 --> 28:45.955
and the people can decide
either I'm wrong

28:46.960 --> 28:50.873
or there's something going on inside
the government that's really wrong.

28:54.680 --> 28:55.715
So...

28:58.280 --> 29:00.999
This one
is everything I have

29:01.080 --> 29:03.992
on your British
intelligence agency, the GCHQ.

29:04.080 --> 29:06.036
An encryption key
will follow.

29:07.200 --> 29:09.714
You're gonna want your technical
people at the Guardian

29:09.800 --> 29:11.040
to look through
that thoroughly.

29:11.080 --> 29:12.991
There's a lot
of stuff there.

29:16.000 --> 29:17.513
Listen,
they're gonna investigate,

29:17.640 --> 29:20.598
and they're gonna
figure out what I've done.

29:20.880 --> 29:22.791
And then they're
gonna come for me.

29:22.880 --> 29:24.438
And now that
we've made contact,

29:26.200 --> 29:27.997
they're gonna come
for all of you, too.

29:33.240 --> 29:35.754
Uh... Um...

29:37.280 --> 29:38.920
Do you mind if I go
look in the microwave?

29:48.120 --> 29:51.237
Ewen. I'm on with Stuart.

29:51.320 --> 29:52.355
Hi, Ewen.

29:52.960 --> 29:56.316
Hi, Stuart. Look,
I've got one thing to say.

29:56.520 --> 29:58.909
- The Guinness here is great.
- Wonderful.

29:59.000 --> 30:01.116
Oh, absolutely
the genuine article.

30:01.200 --> 30:02.315
Good.

30:02.400 --> 30:04.834
But shockingly different
from what you'd expect.

30:05.400 --> 30:10.633
So... Now we have the lawyers
to deal with. And no doubt the White House.

30:12.440 --> 30:13.440
I got the go ahead.

30:13.520 --> 30:14.794
That's great.
Oh, good.

30:14.880 --> 30:16.696
Let's get started. We have
a lot to go through here,

30:16.720 --> 30:18.039
and it's not easy reading.

30:18.120 --> 30:19.917
We can start
by showing him XKeyscore.

30:20.000 --> 30:22.376
Good idea. Ed, can you bring it
up again and walk us through it?

30:22.400 --> 30:23.469
Yeah.

30:30.320 --> 30:32.231
Do we all get
under there now?

30:32.360 --> 30:34.590
He's protecting his passwords.

30:35.680 --> 30:37.875
Okay. So...

30:41.200 --> 30:43.919
This was introduced

30:44.000 --> 30:48.516
during my first deployment
at the CIA in Geneva.

30:48.600 --> 30:49.715
"XKeyscore."

30:51.280 --> 30:52.599
What does that do?

30:52.920 --> 30:55.753
It's like
a search interface.

30:57.480 --> 30:59.072
What does it search for?

30:59.360 --> 31:00.952
Anything you want.

31:02.200 --> 31:03.997
What was your
assignment in Geneva?

31:04.400 --> 31:09.269
Well, I was assigned with
diplomatic cover to the UN mission

31:09.360 --> 31:11.920
to maintain the CIA's
computer security network.

31:16.200 --> 31:20.193
I spent almost two years
around CIA field officers.

31:22.760 --> 31:24.990
I don't see a time
stamp on any of this.

31:25.160 --> 31:26.639
We have
a confirmation on the GSS.

31:28.160 --> 31:30.674
I'm sorry, sir,
I don't understand.

31:30.760 --> 31:33.320
Sherman says you hacked
the Human Resources site.

31:33.440 --> 31:35.237
Yeah, it's my job
to find flaws.

31:35.480 --> 31:37.994
The security of the HR site
is not your problem.

31:38.080 --> 31:39.638
You went outside
the wheelhouse.

31:39.720 --> 31:42.154
Okay, but just to clarify,
I did not hack it,

31:42.320 --> 31:44.709
I showed that it
could be hacked.

31:44.840 --> 31:46.114
You told me
to find a patch.

31:46.200 --> 31:47.349
You have that
in writing?

31:47.440 --> 31:50.637
Yes, I do. Remember, I sent
you the proof of concept.

31:53.800 --> 31:55.056
Doesn't matter
what you did, Snowden.

31:55.080 --> 31:57.880
Right or wrong, you need to let these
things be someone else's problem.

31:58.000 --> 31:59.592
He's also put
a derog in your file.

31:59.680 --> 32:01.079
Excuse me?
Let that be a lesson.

32:01.160 --> 32:02.513
I don't want him
calling me again

32:02.600 --> 32:04.318
about another
Ed Snowden moment.

32:05.400 --> 32:06.799
Okay?

32:10.160 --> 32:11.896
Why don't you take it easy
the rest of the day?

32:11.920 --> 32:13.751
Go work on
the scrubbing pile.

32:19.680 --> 32:21.352
That didn't look
like it went well.

32:21.440 --> 32:26.719
Oh, hey, man. Uh, yeah. No, I just
got a derog for doing my job.

32:26.840 --> 32:30.389
Politics, man. The
culture of fear wins again.

32:30.520 --> 32:32.875
I can't get anything done here.
Yeah.

32:33.320 --> 32:36.949
Hey, um, what about that idea
that we were talking about?

32:37.040 --> 32:38.696
I'm working on it.
I'm waiting for a call back

32:38.720 --> 32:40.199
from our friend
at The Hill.

32:40.240 --> 32:41.992
Who, Corbin? You called Corbin?
Hmm.

32:42.080 --> 32:43.433
You think he can
do something?

32:43.520 --> 32:46.512
We'll see. Maybe some limited
field ops under my supervision.

32:46.600 --> 32:48.176
Yes, that would be amazing.
I would love...

32:48.200 --> 32:51.954
Easy, Ed. I've gotta see a cleric in Milan.
We'll talk after.

32:52.040 --> 32:53.871
Okay. Thank you.

33:12.400 --> 33:14.789
Damn, CIA does not like
to leave a trace, huh?

33:14.880 --> 33:15.880
Can I help you?

33:15.960 --> 33:17.678
You get curious
to check one out?

33:18.160 --> 33:20.276
See what kind of crazy-ass
covert kill mission

33:20.360 --> 33:21.536
you might be erasing
from history?

33:21.560 --> 33:22.640
I'm sorry,
who are you with?

33:22.920 --> 33:25.434
No Such Agency.
I'm Gabriel Sol.

33:25.560 --> 33:28.836
I'm the 50-pound brain from the
Council of Wizards and Warlocks.

33:29.480 --> 33:30.629
Excuse me?

33:30.720 --> 33:32.915
Giving you your intel for
Bucharest, dude. Oh.

33:33.000 --> 33:34.911
Unless there's
another Dave Churchyard.

33:35.000 --> 33:37.639
No. That's me.
Right this way.

33:41.960 --> 33:44.269
I'll be right outside.
Stay if you want.

33:44.360 --> 33:48.876
Uh, I don't have
authorization to use NSA programs.

33:48.960 --> 33:50.096
Well, if you're
the messenger to Bucharest,

33:50.120 --> 33:51.519
you must have
a PRIVAC clearance

33:51.600 --> 33:53.238
to see the finished
intel, yes?

33:54.080 --> 33:55.080
Yeah...

33:55.120 --> 33:56.336
Yeah, so what
difference does it make

33:56.360 --> 33:57.640
if you see how
it's put together?

34:00.240 --> 34:01.798
Well, it's up to you, man.

34:07.200 --> 34:09.315
Uh, you're giving me
just names?

34:09.440 --> 34:10.953
Uh, and a lot more
than names.

34:11.400 --> 34:14.437
What I will be providing you and the
fine gentlemen of the Secret Service

34:14.520 --> 34:19.389
is a list of every threat made about
the President since February 3rd.

34:19.480 --> 34:21.947
And a profile of
every threat-maker.

34:22.880 --> 34:26.873
And these are, like,
existing targets?

34:27.000 --> 34:30.150
99% are gonna come from the
bulk collection program, so...

34:30.320 --> 34:32.117
Upstream, Muscular,
Tempora, PRISM.

34:33.000 --> 34:34.000
PRISM?

34:36.000 --> 34:37.831
You got a little
Snow White in you.

34:38.960 --> 34:42.190
Which makes me feel like the witch
bringing you a poisoned apple.

34:42.280 --> 34:44.589
Here. Exhibit A.

34:44.679 --> 34:47.877
Oakland resident Justin Pinsky
posted on a message board,

34:47.960 --> 34:50.713
"Romania has a storied history
of executing their leaders,

34:50.800 --> 34:53.632
"couldn't they do us a solid
and take out Bush?"

34:54.760 --> 34:57.513
Now this looks juicy.
This is from a G-chat.

34:59.360 --> 35:02.830
"...with the biggest python
you've ever seen." Hmm.

35:04.520 --> 35:06.351
How is this all possible?

35:06.440 --> 35:08.431
Um, keyword selectors.

35:08.520 --> 35:10.670
"Attack," "take out Bush."

35:12.480 --> 35:14.038
So think of it as
a Google search,

35:14.120 --> 35:16.136
except instead of searching
only what people make public,

35:16.160 --> 35:18.355
we're also looking at
everything they don't. So...

35:18.880 --> 35:20.757
Emails, chats,
SMS, whatever.

35:20.840 --> 35:22.512
Yeah, but which people?

35:23.800 --> 35:25.552
The whole kingdom,
Snow White.

35:32.800 --> 35:34.472
Which ambassador
was he again?

35:34.560 --> 35:37.120
De La Hoya, with
World Trade Organization.

35:37.200 --> 35:38.315
Right.

35:52.160 --> 35:53.160
So...

35:53.920 --> 35:55.592
O'Brian came through
for you.

35:55.760 --> 35:59.389
He agrees your talents are being wasted.
You ready for a little action?

36:00.200 --> 36:02.760
Really? What,
you mean right here?

36:03.240 --> 36:05.151
Yeah. Now.

36:05.240 --> 36:07.310
See the woman in
the pink number?

36:07.400 --> 36:12.155
Credit Suisse. J.P. Morgan's on her arm.
Grandma's with Deutsche Bank.

36:12.240 --> 36:14.071
Ten thousand bankers
in this town.

36:14.160 --> 36:16.071
All you need to turn is one.

36:16.680 --> 36:18.272
Socialize. Meet a few.

36:18.360 --> 36:21.079
Preferably ones sitting on
a pile of dirty Saudi money

36:21.160 --> 36:22.559
that's funding bin Laden.

36:22.680 --> 36:25.911
Thank you very much. Church.
Church. Sure. Churchyard.

36:33.800 --> 36:36.519
Mr. Debrinin asks
your business card, please.

36:36.960 --> 36:39.269
An ambassador. Wow!

36:39.480 --> 36:41.357
I wish I had your
schmoozing skills.

36:41.440 --> 36:43.271
Uh, well,
that's why you have me.

36:43.400 --> 36:46.119
Yeah. You don't know any
bankers, do you? Bankers?

36:46.960 --> 36:49.428
Are you on some kind of
assignment or something?

36:50.960 --> 36:55.238
Um, "Relationship cultivating."
And not well.

36:56.760 --> 36:58.034
Let me help you.

36:58.120 --> 36:59.235
No.
Yeah.

36:59.520 --> 37:01.829
No, this is serious.
I know it's serious.

37:02.160 --> 37:03.160
Trust me.

37:05.200 --> 37:06.474
Any luck?

37:06.800 --> 37:07.994
No, no bites.

37:09.520 --> 37:11.829
Is there some kind
of trick to it?

37:12.560 --> 37:14.790
It's all about finding
the pressure point.

37:14.920 --> 37:16.956
Everything else is
just pushing on it.

37:19.600 --> 37:21.158
Looks like
you're being summoned.

37:26.120 --> 37:28.680
...we have to pay extra...
Marwan? May I interrupt?

37:28.760 --> 37:29.909
This is
my boyfriend, Dave.

37:30.000 --> 37:32.514
Hello, Dave. Nice to meet you.
Nice to meet you.

37:32.600 --> 37:33.669
Marwan works at Monfort.

37:34.760 --> 37:37.228
We were talking,
and after last week,

37:37.320 --> 37:39.117
he may be able
to give you some tips.

37:39.200 --> 37:41.760
Gentlemen, I'll see you inside.
Last week?

37:43.440 --> 37:46.671
He's embarrassed. It was
a lot of money for us.

37:49.000 --> 37:51.230
Day trading is a perilous sport.

37:51.360 --> 37:53.715
You shouldn't be ashamed of it.
Yeah.

37:54.440 --> 37:57.113
I'm gonna grab some food.
See you guys inside?

37:57.200 --> 37:58.315
Sure.

38:00.000 --> 38:02.468
You have a lovely girlfriend.
Thank you so much.

38:03.600 --> 38:05.556
You know, I work in IT,
and so I just figured

38:05.720 --> 38:08.393
I could crack the market
like a weak network.

38:08.520 --> 38:11.592
May I ask, how precipitous
were your losses?

38:12.840 --> 38:15.479
Well, I told Lindsay
it was 20,000,

38:15.560 --> 38:18.393
but between you and me,
it was closer to 45.

38:19.200 --> 38:22.636
Tried to recoup,
but that was a mistake,

38:22.720 --> 38:24.312
and now without
any real grounding,

38:24.400 --> 38:26.016
I feel like I'm just
sliding out of control.

38:26.040 --> 38:27.917
Oh, I have seen it
many times.

38:28.000 --> 38:29.797
And I'm always happy
to help a man

38:29.880 --> 38:32.155
break a bad habit
before it gets going.

38:32.240 --> 38:34.071
Oh, thank you.
I really appreciate that.

38:36.400 --> 38:39.153
This is the cleanest
Pakistani I've ever seen.

38:39.240 --> 38:41.390
We got no first-degree ties
to government or ISI,

38:41.480 --> 38:42.913
no shady family.

38:44.000 --> 38:45.736
I mean, second-degree contacts
are off the charts,

38:45.760 --> 38:47.376
but that's... I mean, that's
everyone in the Middle East

38:47.400 --> 38:48.674
with a six-figure income.

38:48.760 --> 38:52.514
Well, it's not dirt that we need
necessarily, it's a pressure point.

38:52.640 --> 38:55.757
Something intimate,
some kind of weakness.

38:55.880 --> 38:59.111
Can we look through his family?
Mmm-hmm.

38:59.840 --> 39:03.594
How about
his sister-in-law?

39:04.880 --> 39:05.915
Yeah.

39:08.520 --> 39:11.796
What is that, is that some
video that she sent somebody?

39:11.880 --> 39:14.269
No, this is live.
Out of Paris.

39:14.560 --> 39:15.754
What do you mean, live?

39:16.600 --> 39:19.558
Optic Nerve. It's
camera and mic activation.

39:19.720 --> 39:21.760
I wish we could take credit,
but the Brits wrote it.

39:21.800 --> 39:23.153
Activation?

39:23.240 --> 39:25.151
Yeah,
her laptop's off.

39:25.240 --> 39:26.878
Or was, she just
forgot to close it.

39:26.960 --> 39:28.056
Of course,
how would she know?

39:28.080 --> 39:30.594
This shit is so sly, the webcam
light doesn't even turn on.

39:38.160 --> 39:41.197
Hmm. I always wondered
what was under those.

39:48.760 --> 39:51.194
Okay, look, let's stick
to family in Geneva.

39:51.440 --> 39:52.714
All right?

39:52.800 --> 39:54.791
Okay, Snow White.
Uh...

39:55.640 --> 39:58.313
Fifteen-year-old daughter
at the International School.

39:58.400 --> 40:02.712
Yeah. Uh, Facebook?
Is that possible?

40:02.800 --> 40:04.472
Dude,
Facebook's my bitch.

40:04.560 --> 40:06.039
Seriously?

40:06.320 --> 40:09.471
Like, she fights
with her parents, or...

40:09.560 --> 40:12.870
Don't worry, don't worry. I know all
the hooks for this kind of fishing.

40:13.480 --> 40:17.314
Uh, query name. So email, keyword,
whatever selector you want.

40:18.000 --> 40:21.151
And justification
is where I write...

40:23.440 --> 40:26.557
In other words, turning your
daddy into a CIA informant.

40:26.680 --> 40:28.796
- Wait, that's it?
- That's it, bro.

40:29.600 --> 40:32.478
You don't have to get
a FISA court order?

40:32.920 --> 40:35.434
Mmm-mmm. No, not here.
XKeyscore's under 702 authority,

40:35.520 --> 40:37.351
which means no warrants.

40:37.600 --> 40:41.115
Okay, but U.S. targets then, you'd
have to get the court order?

40:41.200 --> 40:44.715
You mean FISA? Yeah, they're just
a big-ass rubber stamp, dude.

40:44.800 --> 40:46.472
I mean, FISA judges
are all appointed by

40:46.560 --> 40:49.154
the Chief Justice,
who's like, you know...

40:50.480 --> 40:53.233
Darth Vader when it comes
to national security. Boom.

40:53.760 --> 40:55.193
Here we go.

40:57.240 --> 41:02.678
Okay, okay. And the boy
at third base is...

41:04.880 --> 41:10.034
Nadim. Okay. He's 18.

41:11.360 --> 41:12.496
Salma says she wants
to marry him,

41:12.520 --> 41:14.317
but is scared of
telling her parents.

41:14.480 --> 41:19.713
What she doesn't know is that
his other name is Nicolas.

41:21.280 --> 41:23.555
And he's currently banging
Geraldine and Julie.

41:25.600 --> 41:26.669
And...

41:31.520 --> 41:33.590
He and his Turkish mother
are here illegally.

41:38.920 --> 41:39.955
That's it.

41:48.480 --> 41:50.516
Ah, you like that?

41:50.600 --> 41:52.113
I love these.

41:55.400 --> 41:56.913
Man, what are
we doing here?

41:57.440 --> 41:59.795
You're making people
very happy.

41:59.880 --> 42:02.394
Mr. Marwan's bank
handles serious Saudi money,

42:02.480 --> 42:04.755
and a whole bunch of
Russian billionaires.

42:04.840 --> 42:09.072
What about any al-Qaeda money?
Anything promising?

42:10.440 --> 42:12.670
Ed, I'm up for
a promotion soon.

42:12.800 --> 42:14.631
I will not forget
my friends.

42:15.440 --> 42:16.759
Thank you.

42:16.800 --> 42:18.416
This is all going kind of
fast though, right?

42:18.440 --> 42:20.351
I mean, I just sent
some initial background.

42:20.440 --> 42:22.590
There he is!
The man!

42:22.680 --> 42:23.908
Hey, Marwan!

42:24.000 --> 42:27.151
Dave. How wonderful
to see you.

42:27.240 --> 42:28.514
Good to see you, too.

42:28.640 --> 42:33.430
Uh, I was counting, Marwan, you snuck
in an extra half hour back there.

42:33.520 --> 42:37.354
I'm afraid she was merely
listening to an old man's woes.

42:37.440 --> 42:38.440
Oh, I see.

42:38.520 --> 42:40.351
So, how are you,
Marwan?

42:42.600 --> 42:46.036
I must tell you,
Dave, since we met,

42:46.800 --> 42:49.997
my life has gone
somewhat topsy-turvy.

42:51.320 --> 42:53.151
Oh, no,
I'm sorry to hear that.

42:53.640 --> 42:55.232
But your colleague
Charles here

42:55.320 --> 42:57.515
has graciously
offered his help.

42:57.600 --> 42:59.909
So I owe him and you
a great deal.

43:00.000 --> 43:01.718
Can I ask
what happened?

43:03.320 --> 43:05.914
My daughter had an...

43:06.000 --> 43:08.958
Marwan's daughter
took too many sleeping pills.

43:09.040 --> 43:10.632
She's all right.

43:10.720 --> 43:13.632
It had something to do with her
boyfriend, who was recently deported.

43:13.720 --> 43:15.631
We're trying to secure
a visa for him.

43:15.720 --> 43:19.190
And even so,
I'm afraid that Salma will...

43:21.200 --> 43:23.589
I'm sorry. I won't trouble
you with such matters.

43:23.680 --> 43:27.514
No, no, you... Hey. You
talk as much as you want.

43:27.600 --> 43:30.273
All right?
Family comes first.

43:40.920 --> 43:42.148
Whoa!
Oh!

43:43.040 --> 43:44.234
There's my beauty.

43:46.400 --> 43:48.152
I'm never
like this before.

43:48.240 --> 43:50.071
Oh, sure.
No, of course.

43:50.160 --> 43:52.310
You sit down, huh?
Sit tight.

43:54.040 --> 43:56.873
You sit tight.

43:59.040 --> 44:00.473
What the fuck's
going on?

44:00.560 --> 44:02.516
I have been acting
swiftly and effectively

44:02.600 --> 44:05.637
on the very good signals
intelligence you've provided.

44:05.960 --> 44:08.155
And if his daughter
had died?

44:08.240 --> 44:09.992
We could have
used that too.

44:10.080 --> 44:12.150
Are you serious? What, in
the name of a promotion?

44:15.240 --> 44:18.676
Marwan can't be away
from his family right now.

44:18.800 --> 44:20.995
So in the morning, when
he's facing a week in jail,

44:21.080 --> 44:24.152
we're going to offer him a deal
and he won't turn it down.

44:24.240 --> 44:25.389
Wait, jail? For what?

44:26.400 --> 44:27.549
Drunk driving.

44:27.640 --> 44:29.995
Now, I want you
to call the police.

44:30.080 --> 44:31.376
Tell 'em you saw
a Mercedes headed north...

44:31.400 --> 44:32.628
No, he's not driving
right now.

44:32.720 --> 44:34.517
Look at him,
he'll kill himself.

44:37.600 --> 44:39.431
Okay. I'll call 'em.
Hey!

44:40.920 --> 44:42.069
He's not driving.

44:43.120 --> 44:46.908
Remind me, are you authorized on
any of the NSA programs you used?

44:49.280 --> 44:51.400
So we're both doing a little
fucked up shit here, huh?

44:52.720 --> 44:55.075
Watch yourself, Ed.
I will tell him who you are.

44:56.600 --> 44:59.353
You reveal the identity
of an undercover officer,

44:59.440 --> 45:02.113
you're going to jail
for a lot longer than Marwan.

45:08.440 --> 45:09.440
Hey!

45:23.160 --> 45:24.275
Hey.

45:24.840 --> 45:26.159
Sorry I'm so late.

45:28.960 --> 45:30.279
How was work?

45:32.760 --> 45:34.079
It was, uh...

45:35.840 --> 45:38.149
It was all right. Yeah.

45:39.560 --> 45:42.791
I have to
wake up in, like, three hours.

45:42.880 --> 45:44.313
My flight's at 7:00.

45:47.680 --> 45:49.636
Well, we'd better
be quick, then.

46:35.560 --> 46:38.836
I will provide our intelligence
and law enforcement agencies

46:38.920 --> 46:41.718
with the tools they need to track
and take out the terrorists

46:41.840 --> 46:44.798
without undermining our
constitution and our freedom.

46:45.720 --> 46:47.536
That means no
more illegal wiretapping

46:47.560 --> 46:48.788
of American citizens.

46:48.880 --> 46:52.156
No more ignoring the law
when it is inconvenient.

46:52.240 --> 46:53.639
That is not who we are.

46:54.080 --> 46:55.308
Hey, hon.
Hey.

46:55.720 --> 46:58.518
What happened
to the London trip?

46:58.640 --> 47:00.471
Uh...

47:00.960 --> 47:02.393
Turns out I'm not going.

47:03.360 --> 47:04.509
Oh.

47:06.120 --> 47:08.031
What's going on?
Who's winning?

47:08.120 --> 47:10.256
...and Michelle Obama
voted this morning in Chicago.

47:10.280 --> 47:11.720
- I voted.
- In Arizona...

47:11.920 --> 47:13.035
Still early.

47:13.120 --> 47:15.336
...John and Cindy McCain voted,
and then they landed in Colorado

47:15.360 --> 47:17.157
to defend a traditionally
Republican state

47:17.240 --> 47:18.673
that has turned
into a battleground.

47:18.760 --> 47:19.760
Hey. Let's see.

47:20.200 --> 47:23.397
Obama ahead 67% to 32%...

47:23.480 --> 47:26.597
Come on, big ears.
Check out Florida.

47:31.760 --> 47:33.876
Holy shit, he's gonna win it!

47:34.280 --> 47:36.350
What, Florida?
Yeah!

47:36.440 --> 47:38.431
That's big. Yeah.
It's huge!

47:40.120 --> 47:43.510
You can act all nonchalant, but I know
you were starting to root for him.

47:44.400 --> 47:46.311
I've been watching
your inner liberal grow.

47:46.400 --> 47:48.600
For which I will take a modest
percentage of the credit.

47:48.640 --> 47:50.676
And you deserve it.

47:54.240 --> 47:55.275
What is this?

47:55.360 --> 47:56.588
...in Missouri.

47:56.760 --> 47:59.354
56% for McCain,
43% for Obama.

47:59.480 --> 48:02.950
Oh, yeah, that. Just... Leave that there.
That's, uh...

48:04.480 --> 48:07.040
Russian hackers.
The Agency says

48:07.120 --> 48:09.680
they can activate
webcams now. So...

48:09.760 --> 48:10.760
That's creepy.

48:10.840 --> 48:13.070
Yes. It's really
bothering me.

48:14.320 --> 48:16.800
Whatever. It's not a big deal.
You shouldn't let it bother you.

48:16.840 --> 48:18.558
It's not a big deal? No.

48:18.640 --> 48:20.995
What, that someone could
be watching you right now?

48:21.600 --> 48:24.273
No, I'm not
hiding anything.

48:25.400 --> 48:28.995
That's such
a bullshit line. What is?

48:29.120 --> 48:31.509
I have nothing to hide.
I don't.

48:31.600 --> 48:32.794
Everyone does.

48:33.560 --> 48:35.869
Okay, well then,
what do I have to hide?

48:36.640 --> 48:38.710
Forget it. No,
what do I have to hide?

48:38.800 --> 48:40.631
No, never...
Let's just drop it.

48:40.720 --> 48:44.030
Well, apparently you think that I'm
hiding something, so...

48:44.120 --> 48:46.554
Okay, the other day,
your computer was open,

48:46.640 --> 48:49.438
and I happened to notice you
were on the site where we met,

48:49.520 --> 48:50.816
and you were looking
at other guys.

48:50.840 --> 48:52.990
You just were looking
at my computer?

48:53.840 --> 48:55.216
I wouldn't have
even brought this up.

48:55.240 --> 48:57.231
You asked me,
"What do I have to hide?"

48:57.320 --> 48:59.311
That's something
you're not telling me.

49:01.200 --> 49:05.751
Well, it's not...
I don't do anything,

49:05.880 --> 49:08.075
I don't meet any
of those people.

49:11.160 --> 49:12.798
You're gone for weeks
at a time.

49:12.920 --> 49:15.354
So it's like I'm peering
into other peoples' lives

49:15.480 --> 49:17.471
because my own is
just temporarily on hold.

49:18.720 --> 49:20.039
That sounds like
an excuse.

49:21.160 --> 49:22.354
It's the truth.

49:38.840 --> 49:42.355
I should have told you.
And I didn't.

49:42.440 --> 49:46.069
I'm really sorry.
But it's not a big deal.

49:50.920 --> 49:51.920
Hey.

50:01.080 --> 50:04.629
Look at me.
I don't want anyone else.

50:06.480 --> 50:08.152
I don't want
any other life.

50:09.760 --> 50:10.795
Okay?

50:25.520 --> 50:26.953
Listen, uh...

50:29.200 --> 50:32.510
I didn't go to London today
'cause I resigned.

50:34.680 --> 50:35.749
What?

50:36.160 --> 50:37.991
It was personal differences,

50:38.080 --> 50:40.150
and it was a matter
of principle.

50:41.280 --> 50:42.872
Can you tell me
anything else?

50:46.600 --> 50:47.919
Do you get
reposted, or...

50:48.000 --> 50:50.639
No, no, I resigned
from the CIA.

50:52.160 --> 50:54.151
So what does
that mean? What do we do?

50:54.280 --> 50:57.670
I don't know. I'll figure
it out, but listen, I...

51:00.240 --> 51:03.596
This is a good thing.
Trust me.

51:08.280 --> 51:09.474
I do.

51:20.200 --> 51:21.838
Hey.
Hmm?

51:22.280 --> 51:23.429
He's gonna win.

51:25.040 --> 51:26.656
52% for Obama,
48% for McCain.

51:26.680 --> 51:27.874
Yeah, he'd better.

51:29.160 --> 51:33.073
CNN can now project that
Barack Obama, 47 years old,

51:33.160 --> 51:35.879
will become the President of the
United States.

51:36.480 --> 51:39.950
Every agency and department
should know that this administration

51:40.040 --> 51:41.314
stands on the side

51:41.400 --> 51:43.516
not of those who seek
to withhold information,

51:43.600 --> 51:45.431
but those who seek
to make it known.

51:48.120 --> 51:49.951
Janine is
the website editor

51:50.040 --> 51:52.998
of a small stateside office
of a British newspaper,

51:53.080 --> 51:55.594
up against the most powerful
government in the world.

51:55.680 --> 51:56.954
She won't be bullied.

51:57.360 --> 51:59.396
We need to establish
that we're not compromising

51:59.480 --> 52:01.311
national security
by publishing.

52:01.400 --> 52:02.958
We need
to have alternatives.

52:03.040 --> 52:04.359
Listen, Ed,

52:04.440 --> 52:06.829
the real issue here is that
they, the White House,

52:06.920 --> 52:10.196
are aware that Janine has a leaked
top secret FISA court order.

52:10.280 --> 52:11.474
Anything could happen.

52:11.560 --> 52:12.959
They could subpoena
the Guardian

52:13.040 --> 52:14.176
and, for that matter,
they could

52:14.200 --> 52:15.560
break through
that door any minute,

52:15.640 --> 52:17.596
ending all of this.

52:17.680 --> 52:19.875
We are running
out of time.

52:19.960 --> 52:23.032
We seriously have to think about
doing this on our own website.

52:23.160 --> 52:24.434
We have no choice.

52:24.520 --> 52:26.317
Wait, you can't just
start dumping articles

52:26.440 --> 52:28.237
on the Internet, Glenn!
Be serious.

52:28.320 --> 52:30.993
Look at WikiLeaks.
It destroyed their credibility.

52:31.080 --> 52:32.638
Look, Ed,
you said it yourself,

52:32.720 --> 52:36.156
if this isn't done properly,
the world isn't gonna take notice.

52:36.240 --> 52:39.596
You need experienced
journalists to lead the public

52:39.680 --> 52:42.148
through some very,
very complicated stories.

52:42.240 --> 52:43.753
We are
experienced journalists.

52:44.320 --> 52:45.673
My feeling...

52:52.960 --> 52:56.157
Has anyone called here before?
Not once. Not in three weeks.

52:56.240 --> 52:57.832
Well, I'll...
Shall I answer it?

52:57.960 --> 52:59.598
I'll tell 'em it's
the wrong number.

53:01.280 --> 53:02.429
Yes?

53:03.920 --> 53:05.353
No, I don't.

53:06.960 --> 53:08.439
Okay. Thank you.

53:11.280 --> 53:13.191
Asking if I want
turndown service.

53:13.280 --> 53:15.748
She said the "Do not disturb"
sign was off the door.

53:33.880 --> 53:35.029
So?

53:36.240 --> 53:39.312
Do we wait?
Or go on our own?

53:41.040 --> 53:42.240
Look, I said
from the beginning

53:42.320 --> 53:45.312
that how you publish
is your business,

53:45.400 --> 53:47.152
and I trust you.

53:47.240 --> 53:49.959
The only thing I ask is you study
the data, you be responsible,

53:50.080 --> 53:52.719
no names, no specifics,
anything ongoing

53:52.800 --> 53:54.950
that's critical,
you don't release.

53:55.040 --> 53:57.429
You just stick to the issue
of mass surveillance

53:57.520 --> 53:58.560
and let the people decide.

53:58.640 --> 54:01.800
You have our word on that, but
that's not the question. We have to ask...

54:01.840 --> 54:03.478
Look, Ed, Ed,

54:03.560 --> 54:05.949
right now the White House is
arranging a conference call

54:06.040 --> 54:08.110
between Janine and
the intelligence services.

54:08.200 --> 54:11.272
Now that's gonna happen
in a few hours.

54:11.360 --> 54:15.239
Let's at least wait for that,
see what they say to her.

54:19.840 --> 54:21.876
I'd say we pause a moment.

54:23.160 --> 54:24.616
Yeah, I think
we should reassemble

54:24.640 --> 54:26.176
in this room after
the call takes place,

54:26.200 --> 54:29.829
so that's around midnight.
Be noon in New York.

54:30.600 --> 54:32.113
All right.

54:32.200 --> 54:34.509
I'll take another pass at the
PRISM story in the meantime.

54:34.600 --> 54:38.479
Okay. We'll be in our hotel
room if you need us, okay?

54:38.560 --> 54:39.560
Thanks, Ewen.

54:39.640 --> 54:40.789
Yeah.
Okay.

54:48.400 --> 54:51.198
Uh, do you mind maybe
we take a break from that?

54:51.520 --> 54:53.078
For a second?

54:54.360 --> 54:56.669
Oh, yeah. Sure, sorry.

54:56.840 --> 55:00.196
You wanna take a look?
Might make you feel better.

55:00.400 --> 55:03.039
Oh. It's not
recording, just on standby.

55:03.120 --> 55:04.473
Okay.

55:06.800 --> 55:10.475
When did this start for you?
Not wanting your photo taken?

55:10.760 --> 55:13.149
Uh, probably in Japan.

55:13.240 --> 55:15.708
I remember every time
a camera got pointed at me,

55:15.800 --> 55:18.155
it was like...
Couldn't breathe.

55:19.160 --> 55:20.593
Why was that?

55:21.080 --> 55:25.437
I probably, uh, spent too much time
looking at other people through cameras.

55:26.560 --> 55:28.869
Japan was your
first NSA job, right?

55:28.960 --> 55:33.909
Yeah, well, as a contractor with Dell.
Had a lot of access.

55:34.400 --> 55:36.391
Why'd you go
back after Geneva?

55:39.520 --> 55:43.149
'Cause the money, and 'cause
I wanted to live in Japan.

55:43.240 --> 55:44.992
And because of Obama,
actually.

55:45.080 --> 55:47.719
You know, I thought things were
gonna get better with him.

55:51.080 --> 55:52.479
I was wrong.

55:58.040 --> 55:59.200
What was it like there?

56:00.280 --> 56:02.236
Well,
in the first part of my day,

56:02.320 --> 56:06.518
I was building this round-the-clock
backup system called Epic Shelter.

56:06.600 --> 56:09.114
So, if there was
some catastrophe,

56:09.200 --> 56:12.078
say, uh, terrorists
burned down every embassy

56:12.160 --> 56:14.720
and NSA post in
the Middle East.

56:14.800 --> 56:19.476
This program would ensure we
wouldn't lose any of that data.

56:19.800 --> 56:23.554
But then, I would have to put it
aside when visitors would show up.

56:23.640 --> 56:24.640
Hi, Ed.

56:24.720 --> 56:29.510
NSA wanted to impress the
Japanese, show them our reach.

56:30.480 --> 56:33.233
They loved
the live drone feeds.

56:33.320 --> 56:35.470
This is over Pakistan.

56:36.400 --> 56:37.719
Right now.

56:40.480 --> 56:43.995
They were not as thrilled to
learn that we wanted them to help us

56:44.080 --> 56:46.196
spy on
the Japanese population.

56:47.320 --> 56:50.073
They said it was
against their laws.

56:51.240 --> 56:53.390
Course we tapped
the entire country anyway.

56:54.360 --> 56:56.316
And we didn't stop there,

56:56.400 --> 56:58.550
'cause once we owned
their communications systems,

56:58.640 --> 57:01.552
we started going after
their physical infrastructure.

57:01.640 --> 57:05.918
We'd slip these little sleeper
programs into power grids,

57:06.000 --> 57:07.956
dams, hospitals,

57:08.040 --> 57:10.110
and the idea was
if the day came

57:10.200 --> 57:12.589
when Japan was
no longer an ally,

57:12.680 --> 57:13.999
it'd be lights out.

57:17.200 --> 57:18.474
And it wasn't
just the Japanese.

57:18.560 --> 57:22.075
We were planting malware
in Mexico, Germany,

57:22.160 --> 57:23.832
Brazil, Austria.

57:25.400 --> 57:28.915
I mean, China I can understand,
or Russia, or Iran,

57:29.000 --> 57:31.673
or Venezuela, okay.
But Austria?

57:33.440 --> 57:36.477
You're also being ordered
to follow most world leaders

57:36.560 --> 57:38.152
and heads of industry.

57:38.240 --> 57:41.550
You know, you're tracking
trade deals, sex scandals,

57:41.880 --> 57:44.553
diplomatic cables
to give the U. S.

57:44.640 --> 57:47.108
An advantage in
negotiations at the G8,

57:47.200 --> 57:50.795
or leverage over
Brazilian oil companies,

57:50.880 --> 57:55.032
or helping to oust some third-world
leader who's not playing ball.

57:56.400 --> 57:58.630
And ultimately,
the truth sinks in

57:58.720 --> 58:01.553
that no matter what justification
you're selling yourself,

58:01.640 --> 58:03.915
this is not about terrorism.

58:05.480 --> 58:07.277
Terrorism is the excuse.

58:10.240 --> 58:14.950
This is about economic
and social control.

58:16.560 --> 58:19.074
And the only thing
you're really protecting

58:19.160 --> 58:21.549
is the supremacy
of your government.

58:30.840 --> 58:33.991
Were you thinking about
going to journalists then?

58:34.080 --> 58:37.038
No. No, that wouldn't have
occurred to me back then.

58:38.640 --> 58:42.679
I just thought, you know,
the system will self-correct,

58:42.760 --> 58:46.275
and the President will keep his
promise that got him elected...

58:48.440 --> 58:52.194
That's actually when I first started
reading about you and your films.

58:52.280 --> 58:53.349
It was in Glenn's blog.

58:53.440 --> 58:56.512
You were being detained
in airports for hours.

58:56.600 --> 59:00.434
Thirty-seven times. For investigating
your own country's wars.

59:00.640 --> 59:05.111
That's why I'm going back to Berlin
to edit. You can trust me with this.

59:05.640 --> 59:07.790
I do. Yeah.

59:08.960 --> 59:12.714
I haven't trusted
anyone in years.

59:15.960 --> 59:21.557
It was a welcome change when they
put me on terrorism watch duty.

59:22.240 --> 59:25.915
Every day, I'd go in and I'd get
starting points for SIGINT,

59:26.040 --> 59:28.634
which is signals intelligence.

59:30.160 --> 59:33.914
A lot of them were American,
which felt strange,

59:34.000 --> 59:35.831
but you just keep
reminding yourself,

59:35.920 --> 59:39.913
I could stop a dirty bomb attack
and save thousands of lives.

59:40.560 --> 59:43.950
The thing is, you're not just
following your bad guy targets.

59:44.040 --> 59:46.600
You're also following
their metadata,

59:46.680 --> 59:50.673
which is basically all the phone
numbers that they're in touch with.

59:51.600 --> 59:55.309
Let's say your target
is a shady Iranian banker

59:55.400 --> 59:57.914
operating out of Beirut,
okay.

59:58.000 --> 01:00:00.434
So you're watching his stuff,
but you're also watching

01:00:00.520 --> 01:00:02.954
all the people
that he talks to.

01:00:03.040 --> 01:00:05.634
Including,
you know, his cousin,

01:00:05.720 --> 01:00:08.280
who's just some dentist
living in Buffalo.

01:00:08.360 --> 01:00:11.158
And then you have to watch
all of that guy's contacts.

01:00:11.240 --> 01:00:14.596
And by the time you go a third hop
out from the original target,

01:00:14.680 --> 01:00:20.198
you're watching this bartender
chat with her mother about Botox.

01:00:20.280 --> 01:00:25.274
'Cause three hops from anyone
with, say, 40 contacts,

01:00:25.360 --> 01:00:27.999
you're looking at a list
of 2. 5 million people.

01:00:30.560 --> 01:00:32.676
And there's that
moment when

01:00:32.760 --> 01:00:36.355
you're sitting there and
the scale of it hits you.

01:00:36.440 --> 01:00:41.116
The NSA is really tracking
every cell phone in the world.

01:00:41.240 --> 01:00:43.037
No matter who you are,

01:00:43.160 --> 01:00:45.799
every day of your life,
you're sitting in a database

01:00:45.880 --> 01:00:48.474
just ready
to be looked at.

01:00:59.040 --> 01:01:04.672
And not just terrorists, or
countries, or corporations, but you.

01:01:13.240 --> 01:01:15.276
Was Lindsay with you
in Japan?

01:01:17.080 --> 01:01:20.675
Japan was difficult
for us.

01:01:23.680 --> 01:01:25.636
I guess you couldn't
talk about your work.

01:01:25.840 --> 01:01:27.319
No.

01:01:28.840 --> 01:01:32.549
There was this one night,
uh, towards the end,

01:01:34.280 --> 01:01:37.158
when, uh, we were supposed to go
climb Mount Fuji the next day...

01:01:44.480 --> 01:01:45.480
Wow!

01:01:47.400 --> 01:01:49.868
Are you gonna
post that on Twitter?

01:01:49.960 --> 01:01:50.960
No.

01:01:51.280 --> 01:01:53.714
They're just for me.
What do you think?

01:01:56.320 --> 01:01:58.231
You should delete those.

01:01:58.440 --> 01:02:01.079
That's not quite the artistic
critique I was going for.

01:02:01.360 --> 01:02:03.032
I'm sorry. You just...
You should...

01:02:03.120 --> 01:02:04.976
You can't have stuff like
that on your hard drive.

01:02:05.000 --> 01:02:06.035
Yes, I can.

01:02:06.120 --> 01:02:10.079
Can you just please... I'm
asking you, can you delete them?

01:02:10.840 --> 01:02:12.159
Russian hackers again?

01:02:12.240 --> 01:02:13.275
No...

01:02:15.840 --> 01:02:17.159
Is it us?

01:02:19.960 --> 01:02:21.075
It's classified.

01:02:22.640 --> 01:02:23.868
Am I a target?

01:02:23.960 --> 01:02:25.188
Of course not.

01:02:26.480 --> 01:02:28.755
Clearly someone is looking
at my nude portraits.

01:02:28.840 --> 01:02:30.717
Okay. I shouldn't
have brought it up.

01:02:30.800 --> 01:02:33.109
All right? It's issues
of national security.

01:02:35.200 --> 01:02:37.350
Well, I am flattered
that my boobs

01:02:37.480 --> 01:02:39.311
are considered an issue
of national security,

01:02:39.440 --> 01:02:41.176
but you're gonna have to do
a lot better than that.

01:02:41.200 --> 01:02:43.668
I'd rather not talk about stuff
that could land us in jail.

01:02:43.760 --> 01:02:45.576
So that's what
the Band-Aids are about, then?

01:02:45.600 --> 01:02:47.431
And your camera phobia?

01:02:47.520 --> 01:02:48.714
Because of work?

01:02:49.680 --> 01:02:51.113
Are they watching us?

01:02:51.840 --> 01:02:53.478
Who are they watching?
No one, okay?

01:02:53.560 --> 01:02:55.198
Let's just stop
talking about it.

01:02:56.400 --> 01:02:59.949
Let's go to bed,
and wake up in the morning,

01:03:01.360 --> 01:03:03.635
and go climb this fucking mountain.
All right?

01:03:04.680 --> 01:03:06.176
Of course we're not
gonna talk about it.

01:03:06.200 --> 01:03:07.474
What is that
supposed to mean?

01:03:07.560 --> 01:03:10.028
It means that we don't talk
about anything anymore.

01:03:10.760 --> 01:03:13.354
You work 12-hour days,
you come home depressed,

01:03:13.440 --> 01:03:15.795
you play fucking video games,
and then you fall asleep.

01:03:15.880 --> 01:03:17.552
Yeah, I'm tired
'cause I have a job.

01:03:17.640 --> 01:03:19.039
That's what pays
for this apartment

01:03:19.120 --> 01:03:20.838
in the most expensive city
in the world.

01:03:20.920 --> 01:03:24.151
Which you asked me to come to knowing
that I did not have a work visa.

01:03:24.240 --> 01:03:25.468
Okay, what if
you had one?

01:03:25.560 --> 01:03:29.075
Would you really give up your
beautiful life of eating and sleeping

01:03:29.200 --> 01:03:31.760
and going out all the time? You
think you'd really want a career?

01:03:31.800 --> 01:03:35.156
A career like yours? Where I'm
miserable all the time? No.

01:03:35.240 --> 01:03:37.390
That's called
responsibility.

01:03:38.080 --> 01:03:40.150
Fuck this.

01:03:40.240 --> 01:03:42.071
You know what?
You have no fucking idea

01:03:42.160 --> 01:03:44.833
what it's like to be accountable
for other people's lives,

01:03:44.920 --> 01:03:46.990
because you live
in a fairy tale land

01:03:47.080 --> 01:03:48.991
where just there
are no consequences,

01:03:49.080 --> 01:03:50.672
and no one ever gets hurt.

01:03:53.680 --> 01:03:58.071
No. No,
you, you don't get hurt.

01:03:59.600 --> 01:04:00.919
I get
fucking crushed.

01:04:01.040 --> 01:04:02.837
Fucking bullshit!
I've done nothing to you!

01:04:02.920 --> 01:04:04.876
That's exactly right.
You have done nothing!

01:04:05.920 --> 01:04:07.990
You don't hang out with me,
you don't laugh with me,

01:04:08.080 --> 01:04:10.913
you don't even
fucking touch me anymore.

01:04:13.160 --> 01:04:14.388
I'm sorry.
Stop!

01:04:14.960 --> 01:04:16.632
No!

01:04:29.760 --> 01:04:32.115
We, uh, never made it to Mount Fuji.

01:04:33.640 --> 01:04:37.269
And Lindsay left pretty
soon after that, and...

01:04:38.960 --> 01:04:40.518
I was really lonely there.

01:04:42.120 --> 01:04:44.480
But after three months, I left too.
I went back to Maryland.

01:05:12.640 --> 01:05:14.232
And I promised her
I'd change.

01:05:15.240 --> 01:05:17.071
And, uh, we moved
back in together.

01:05:17.160 --> 01:05:18.576
Make
sure your knees stay bent,

01:05:18.600 --> 01:05:21.512
and then you can fully extend
once you feel stable. Ready?

01:05:21.600 --> 01:05:23.636
One, two, three.

01:05:24.320 --> 01:05:25.320
All the way up.

01:05:25.440 --> 01:05:26.976
Now you wanna clench
between your knees.

01:05:27.000 --> 01:05:29.434
It'll burn,
but it's a good burn.

01:05:29.520 --> 01:05:30.520
Perfect.

01:05:30.560 --> 01:05:31.993
Twirl around.

01:05:33.600 --> 01:05:35.830
Perfect! Oh, my
God, I'm so proud of you!

01:05:35.920 --> 01:05:37.751
When you're really happy,

01:05:37.840 --> 01:05:41.196
there's a large part of you
that just wants to stay happy.

01:05:45.360 --> 01:05:48.511
And you start to think, what could
be more important than this?

01:05:49.680 --> 01:05:51.193
What!
Is it okay?

01:05:51.920 --> 01:05:54.036
Oh, my God.
It's so beautiful.

01:05:55.560 --> 01:05:59.633
You know, lots of people
cruise happily through life.

01:06:01.240 --> 01:06:02.719
Why can't I?

01:06:11.720 --> 01:06:13.278
And I went back
to work at the CIA.

01:06:13.440 --> 01:06:15.032
With backdoors...

01:06:15.120 --> 01:06:17.873
My official title was
Solutions Consultant.

01:06:18.840 --> 01:06:22.037
Basically I was hawking
overpriced hardware for a living.

01:06:22.120 --> 01:06:23.792
But I thought
you had resigned?

01:06:23.880 --> 01:06:26.348
Yeah, well, it was all
contract work after Geneva.

01:06:26.440 --> 01:06:28.670
You know,
it's Booz Allen Hamilton,

01:06:28.760 --> 01:06:30.876
or Dell, in partnership

01:06:30.960 --> 01:06:33.997
with CIA or NSA, DIA.

01:06:34.560 --> 01:06:38.633
That's the intelligence
community's revolving door.

01:06:40.160 --> 01:06:42.628
How was it?
Being back in the States?

01:06:43.120 --> 01:06:46.669
It was, uh, it was
really good to be home.

01:06:49.000 --> 01:06:53.118
But Maryland was where things
started to turn for me.

01:06:53.880 --> 01:06:58.556
Every time I felt like I was finally
letting go of all the anxiety

01:06:58.640 --> 01:07:01.234
and all the questions that
used to keep me up at night,

01:07:01.320 --> 01:07:05.233
I'd learn something else,
and I just couldn't ignore it.

01:07:05.440 --> 01:07:09.228
Like, there were these three
high-level officials at the NSA,

01:07:09.320 --> 01:07:12.039
Bill Binney, Ed Loomis,
and Kirk Wiebe.

01:07:12.120 --> 01:07:16.318
They'd been filing complaints about
abuse and overreach for years.

01:07:16.400 --> 01:07:20.188
That's all they did,
they just filed complaints,

01:07:20.280 --> 01:07:23.431
and the FBI
raided their homes.

01:07:23.560 --> 01:07:25.073
Then there was Thomas Drake.

01:07:25.160 --> 01:07:27.116
Like the other three guys,
Drake was trying

01:07:27.200 --> 01:07:29.475
to change things
from the inside.

01:07:29.560 --> 01:07:31.949
But when nothing worked,
he did go to the press.

01:07:32.040 --> 01:07:35.953
So they hit him with the Espionage
Act, and we were shocked.

01:07:36.040 --> 01:07:37.951
The whole intel community.

01:07:38.040 --> 01:07:39.416
Why do you
think you were charged?

01:07:39.440 --> 01:07:40.953
To send a chilling message.

01:07:41.360 --> 01:07:42.360
To whom?

01:07:42.440 --> 01:07:45.000
To other whistleblowers,
to others in the government,

01:07:45.120 --> 01:07:47.190
not to speak out.

01:07:47.280 --> 01:07:51.319
Do not tell truth to power.
We'll hammer you.

01:07:52.920 --> 01:07:55.559
There's a new
program being developed

01:07:55.640 --> 01:07:57.995
at the NSA's op
center on Oahu.

01:07:59.000 --> 01:08:02.549
You'd be going up against
Chinese cyber divisions.

01:08:03.840 --> 01:08:04.989
You interested?

01:08:07.640 --> 01:08:10.916
Won't be the vast sums of
money you're making now,

01:08:11.000 --> 01:08:13.468
but you'd be performing a critical
service for your country.

01:08:13.560 --> 01:08:14.879
I know that's
important to you.

01:08:14.960 --> 01:08:17.269
You mean service
like in Geneva?

01:08:17.359 --> 01:08:20.193
Matt was a mistake. Shouldn't
have pushed you into that.

01:08:20.279 --> 01:08:21.319
You didn't push me
into it.

01:08:21.399 --> 01:08:23.515
I asked for exposure to field
ops, you gave it to me.

01:08:23.600 --> 01:08:25.318
I won't hold that
against you.

01:08:27.359 --> 01:08:29.828
Is there something
you do hold against me?

01:08:33.920 --> 01:08:35.240
You didn't tell me
we were running

01:08:35.279 --> 01:08:37.510
a dragnet on
the whole world, Corbin.

01:09:01.160 --> 01:09:02.388
Great shooting, Ed.

01:09:02.479 --> 01:09:03.799
Thank you.

01:09:04.279 --> 01:09:05.837
That's terrific.

01:09:06.399 --> 01:09:08.709
It's the one thing
in the Army I was good at.

01:09:14.720 --> 01:09:16.438
You ever think, Ed,

01:09:16.520 --> 01:09:21.354
since the Second World War,
it's been 60 years and still no WW III.

01:09:22.279 --> 01:09:23.395
Why?

01:09:24.399 --> 01:09:28.313
Because we've used our power
generally for the good of the world.

01:09:29.040 --> 01:09:31.917
For prosperity, order.

01:09:32.160 --> 01:09:33.877
How can we defend
ourselves against

01:09:33.960 --> 01:09:37.157
nuclear war, terror attacks,
cyber-attacks

01:09:37.240 --> 01:09:39.629
without a centralized
intel factory

01:09:39.720 --> 01:09:41.596
working around the world
night and day?

01:09:42.399 --> 01:09:45.233
So we should catalogue
billions of people's lives?

01:09:45.319 --> 01:09:48.676
Most people already catalogue
their lives for public consumption.

01:09:48.760 --> 01:09:51.911
Well, they catalogue part of their lives,
and they do it by choice.

01:09:52.040 --> 01:09:54.496
We're not giving them the choice.
We're just taking everything.

01:09:54.520 --> 01:09:58.274
Most Americans don't want freedom,
they want security.

01:09:59.120 --> 01:10:00.678
It's a simple bargain. If...

01:10:00.800 --> 01:10:02.756
Good girl! Good girl!

01:10:03.600 --> 01:10:05.352
If you want to play
with all the new toys

01:10:05.440 --> 01:10:08.398
and be safe, you pay
the price of admission.

01:10:10.000 --> 01:10:12.639
Yeah, except people,

01:10:12.720 --> 01:10:14.536
they don't even know
they've made that bargain.

01:10:14.560 --> 01:10:16.790
Where's the modern
battlefield, soldier?

01:10:18.640 --> 01:10:19.640
Everywhere.

01:10:19.960 --> 01:10:22.349
What's
the first rule of battle?

01:10:22.520 --> 01:10:24.112
Never reveal
your position.

01:10:25.080 --> 01:10:29.870
And if one unauthorized person knew?
If Congress knew?

01:10:29.960 --> 01:10:31.712
So would the enemy.

01:10:31.800 --> 01:10:35.839
That, Mr. Snowden,
is the state of the world.

01:10:35.960 --> 01:10:39.589
Secrecy is security,
and security is victory.

01:10:47.320 --> 01:10:48.878
Thank you, sir.

01:10:50.480 --> 01:10:51.708
Someone I want you
to meet.

01:10:51.800 --> 01:10:53.816
Beautiful day for it, wasn't it?
Perfect weather.

01:10:53.840 --> 01:10:56.308
Mr. Lowell. Jim.

01:10:56.800 --> 01:10:58.756
How are you?
Dorian.

01:10:58.840 --> 01:11:00.193
Alan.
Nice to see you.

01:11:00.280 --> 01:11:01.395
Welcome to the U.S.

01:11:01.480 --> 01:11:03.038
How'd you make
out today, Corbin?

01:11:03.160 --> 01:11:05.958
Uh, very mediocre.
Nothing like Ed here.

01:11:06.560 --> 01:11:09.393
Apparently the Army's training
people to shoot straight.

01:11:09.480 --> 01:11:11.277
So this is Ed Snowden.

01:11:11.360 --> 01:11:12.560
Yes, sir.
Pleasure to meet you.

01:11:12.680 --> 01:11:15.069
The brains behind Epic Shelter.
That's right.

01:11:15.160 --> 01:11:16.496
That's brilliant work.
Thank you, sir.

01:11:16.520 --> 01:11:18.016
Yeah, I had a few questions
I wanted to ask you.

01:11:18.040 --> 01:11:20.873
Uh, Jim. Will you
excuse me, gentlemen?

01:11:21.320 --> 01:11:22.719
Excuse me, Alan.
Nice to meet you.

01:11:23.520 --> 01:11:27.991
Yeah, it's proving very useful
to our UAV program.

01:11:28.080 --> 01:11:31.277
Yes, I heard. With foreign
site intel transfer.

01:11:31.360 --> 01:11:32.952
Transfers happen
on collection now.

01:11:33.040 --> 01:11:36.350
They go straight to the Pentagon,
Mossad if they need it.

01:11:36.520 --> 01:11:39.193
Actionable immediately.
No one sees it.

01:11:39.360 --> 01:11:40.634
It's improved
the response time

01:11:40.720 --> 01:11:42.597
of our drone pilots
by a factor of ten.

01:11:43.200 --> 01:11:46.636
Tell me, Ed. You worked signals
intelligence in Japan too, yes?

01:11:46.720 --> 01:11:47.789
Yes, sir.

01:11:47.880 --> 01:11:49.632
How'd you like it?

01:11:49.720 --> 01:11:53.235
It was a very empowering job, sir.

01:11:53.360 --> 01:11:57.512
With this new job in Hawaii,
you'd have even more access.

01:11:57.600 --> 01:12:01.718
I asked Corbin to start the conversation.
But the offer is mine.

01:12:03.760 --> 01:12:05.352
Take your time.

01:12:05.440 --> 01:12:06.616
It's going to
take a few months

01:12:06.640 --> 01:12:08.949
to get this program
on its feet.

01:12:09.040 --> 01:12:11.679
If you'll excuse me,
gentlemen, I see dinner.

01:12:12.800 --> 01:12:14.597
Beer, sir?
Thank you.

01:12:15.280 --> 01:12:17.077
Sir, for you?
Uh, no, thank you.

01:12:22.760 --> 01:12:24.796
Epic Shelter was meant
as a backup program.

01:12:26.080 --> 01:12:29.516
Lowell is creating
this position for you, Ed.

01:12:29.600 --> 01:12:32.194
You'd be the first contractor
outside Fort Meade

01:12:32.280 --> 01:12:33.918
working counter-cyber.

01:12:35.120 --> 01:12:37.190
It's your ticket to the top.

01:12:48.280 --> 01:12:50.016
Do you believe the United States

01:12:50.040 --> 01:12:51.996
is the greatest country
in the world?

01:12:52.080 --> 01:12:53.718
Yes.

01:12:55.240 --> 01:12:56.296
Have you ever used

01:12:56.320 --> 01:12:58.993
any programs
you were unauthorized for?

01:13:04.960 --> 01:13:05.995
No.

01:13:18.440 --> 01:13:21.193
We're not usually
supposed to submit our own work,

01:13:21.280 --> 01:13:24.556
but my editor said
she'd make an exception.

01:13:24.640 --> 01:13:25.675
Pretty neat, huh?

01:13:31.000 --> 01:13:33.150
I get to
submit an entry.

01:13:36.360 --> 01:13:38.954
You ignoring me
on purpose, or what?

01:13:39.040 --> 01:13:41.554
No. Sorry.
Shit. Uh...

01:13:42.000 --> 01:13:44.355
I was just thinking.

01:13:44.480 --> 01:13:45.674
About what?

01:13:50.960 --> 01:13:53.349
I wanted to talk to you
about it at dinner,

01:13:53.440 --> 01:13:55.670
but let's just...
Will you come sit down?

